04760nam a22008055i 9780812294088DE-B159720200826040535.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200826t20172017pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)992489646  a97808122940887 a10.9783/97808122940882doi  a(DE-B1597)481194  a(OCoLC)985319289  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBM506.A17 7aREL0640002bisacsh04a296.12542231 aWasserman, Mira Beth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJews, Gentiles, and Other Animals :bThe Talmud After the Humanities /cMira Beth Wasserman. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDivinations: Rereading Late Ancient Religion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tA Note on Sources, Usage, and Transliteration -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Sense of a Beginning -- t2. Jews, Gentiles, and Other Animals -- t3. Leaky Vessels -- t4. Ethics and Objects -- t5. The Last Laugh -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Jews, Gentiles, and Other Animals, Mira Beth Wasserman undertakes a close reading of Avoda Zara, arguably the Talmud's most scandalous tractate, to uncover the hidden architecture of this classic work of Jewish religious thought. She proposes a new way of reading the Talmud that brings it into conversation with the humanities, including animal studies, the new materialisms, and other areas of critical theory that have been reshaping the understanding of what it is to be a human being.Even as it comments on the the rabbinic laws that govern relations between Jews and non-Jews, Avoda Zara is also an attempt to reflect on what all people share in common, and on how humans fit into a larger universe of animals and things. As is typical of the Talmud in general, it proceeds by incorporating a vast and confusing array of apparently digressive materials, but Wasserman demonstrates that there is a whole greater than the sum of the parts, a sustained effort to explore human identity and difference.In centuries past, Avoda Zara has been a flashpoint in Jewish-Christian relations. It was partly due to its content that the Talmud was subject to burning and censorship by Christian authorities. Wasserman develops a twenty-first-century reading of the tractate that aims to reposition it as part of a broader quest to understand what connects human beings to each other and to the world around them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aGentiles in rabbinical literature 0aJudaismxRelations 0aTheological anthropologyxJudaism 4aJewish Studies. 4aReligion. 4aReligious Studies. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / Talmud.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theology, Relig. Studies, Jewish Studies 2017z9783110548259oZDB-23-DGF08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package 2017z978311055030640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229408840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812294088423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812294088.jpg  a978-3-11-055030-6  Penn Press eBook Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-062526-4  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGFb2017  aZDB-23-DGGb2017